HEADWORD: Plethora
<hw>Pleth"o*ra</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/,
fr. <?/ to be or become full. Cf. <er>Pleonasm</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Overfullness; especially, excessive fullness of the blood vessels;
repletion; that state of the blood vessels or of the system when the
blood exceeds a healthy standard in quantity; hyper⟦ae⟧mia; -- opposed
to <xex>an⟦ae⟧mia</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>State of being overfull; excess;
superabundance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He labors under a <qex>plethora</qex> of wit and imagination.</q>
<rj><qau>Jeffrey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plethoretic</ent>⟦br⟧
